<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON VIEW: AMBASSADOR FROM TURKEY FETED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU LOPER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There wasn't a spot of garden space vacant at the fete honoring the Ambassador 
of the Republic of Turkey to the United States, Nuzhet Kandemir, and his wife, 
Sadiye. Turkish Consul General Mehmet Emre and his wife, Sema, were exuding 
smiles and directing the crowd to the cerkez tavuk (chicken with walnuts), 
doner (beef on a spit), patlican kizartma (eggplant with green chiles), borrek 
(fried pastry) and rice pilav. 
</P>
<P>
Prominent were Mission Viejo real estate broker Vasif Canli, Los Angeles 
developer T.K. Kutay, civil engineer Nezih M. Gunal, Chasen's assistant manager 
Orhan Arli and Turan and Judy Kahraman. 
</P>
<P>
Why the visit? Explained the ambassador: "To explain the business opportunities 
that exist in Turkey." J. Jamison Moore, who owns Atlantis Inc., already knows. 
He and his wife, Mara, have sold their house and will live abroad for the next 
five years to oversee his $552-million resort development near Izmir. Yachting 
was on the minds of Bud and Virginia Carpenter. He's in charge of the Los 
Angeles Yacht Club plans for 75 Southland sailors to sail on seas off the coves 
of Turkey next year. 
</P>
<P>
BOUQUETS: The Friends of Robinson Gardens garden tour has become one of the 
can't-miss events of spring. This year the gardens of Irene Kassorla and Norman 
Friedmann, Stephanie and Louis Snyder, Otis and Dody Booth, Don and Kathleen 
Spiegelman, plus the Virginia Robinson Gardens, were picked by benefit 
co-chairs Carol Mancino and Donna Kamin and co-presidents Donna Wolff and 
Bridget Martens. They also chose famous gardener Georgie Van de Kamp (mother of 
gubernatorial candidate John Van de Kamp) for honorary chair. 
</P>
<P>
WOW! It helps to have former President Ronald Reagan joining entertainers Jose 
Feliciano and Maureen McGovern for fund raising. The folks in the background 
also deserve applause for raising more than $450,000 at the fourth annual "A 
Night Under the Stars" gala to benefit the Muscular Dystrophy Assn. 
</P>
<P>
At the party Mr. Reagan presented August Busch III, chairman of the board and 
president of Anheuser-Busch Companies Inc., with the Dennis Day Memorial Award 
for the $4.7 million he's raised. More in on the fun, Ed McMahon; Jerry Lewis, 
national MDA chair, and comedian Norm Crosby, given the Humanitarian Award. 
</P>
