<HEADLINE>
<P>
REASON AND RHETORIC ON FLAG BURNING AND FREE SPEECH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your excellent picture of a young lady shredding the American flag (front page, 
May 15) is unlikely to send a message to Congress where reason has so obviously 
succumbed to rhetoric. I can appreciate full well what the anguished face in 
the picture is "saying." 
</P>
<P>
Call it symbolic speech or what you will, I "read her lips" as the desperate 
call of an intelligent, conscientious, young person directed to the ruling 
class in this nation to put an end to foreign wars and interventions, to 
restore respect for the Constitution and laws of the United States, and to 
embrace as a plank of our foreign policy the age-old doctrine of the comity of 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
It is a sad reflection of our times that the people who flirt so freely with 
the words "democracy" and "freedom" are hellbent on the incarceration of 
conscientious dissenters. What we don't seem to realize is that we are 
returning to pre-independence days when the British used the sedition laws to 
suppress free speech. 
</P>
<P>
Who would have thought that only a few months ago, Congress gave standing 
ovations to the two greatest dissenters of our times. They, of course, were 
anti-communist dissenters. And that's another story! 
</P>
<P>
LEO NEALON 
</P>
<P>
Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
