<LENGTH>
<P>
658 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
Q &amp; A 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q: What do you think about Pan Am? I hear stories about it taking over another 
airline or another airline taking it over. Is it a good investment? -- Oak 
Lawn, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
A: Pan Am has problems. Even its chairman, G. Thomas Plaskett, has been saying 
publicly for a long time that the best action for Pan Am would be to become 
part of a "larger route network." That means Pan Am needs to combine with one 
or more airlines. 
</P>
<P>
The hottest of the talks, according to a well-informed source, came a few 
months ago when Pan Am was discussing a deal with NWA Corp., the parent of 
Northwest Airlines. Those discussions have virtually ended. 
</P>
<P>
Before that, there were talks with TWA. Carl Icahn, head of TWA, wanted Pan Am 
to purchase his airline, according to a source. With more than $1 billion in 
tax losses to carry forward, Pan Am can offer lower taxes to another airline if 
a merger is structured in which Pan Am is technically the one doing the 
acquiring. 
</P>
<P>
Because fuel costs have declined, airlines are generally making better profits 
these days. So Pan Am could be safe for a while. But next September, the 
airline has a $73-million pension payment due that could stretch its liquidity 
to the limit. Pan Am has requested a waiver on that payment. If it doesn't get 
it, it will probably have to sell an asset. Which one? Its Boston-New 
York-Washington shuttle is a likely candidate. 
</P>
<P>
But even then, Pan Am's problems won't be over. In October, says Thomas Longman 
of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., Pan Am will have to pay big bills that were 
deferred on leased aircraft. Longman thinks that Pan Am will lose $1.40 a share 
this year, better than the $2.31 a share it lost in 1989. According to the 
Institutional Brokers Estimate System computer, the average estimate is a loss 
of $1.76 a share this year. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I read recently that T. Boone Pickens, the corporate raider, said he 
attacked companies first and foremost because he was trying to serve the 
interest of the shareholders of his company, Mesa Petroleum. 
</P>
<P>
I bought Mesa Limited Partnership units at $16 in 1987. They closed recently at 
less than $5. I wonder who Pickens is serving? -- Palm Desert, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
A: T. Boone Pickens did, indeed, say all he was trying to do with his forays 
was serve the interests of Mesa shareholders. But sometimes people just don't 
succeed in following through on their intentions. 
</P>
<P>
David Bradshaw, the energy analyst at Paine Webber Inc., says a lot of Mesa's 
problems weren't caused by Pickens. "The '80s were bad for the energy 
business," Bradshaw says. The price of natural gas, Mesa's main business, 
peaked in 1981 at more than $6 per 1,000 cubic feet. Recently, he says, the 
price was around $1.65. Since Mesa didn't have any refining and marketing 
capabilities, it couldn't insulate itself against such a steep drop in natural 
gas prices. 
</P>
<P>
Bradshaw is neutral on Mesa Limited units. They'll perform no better -- or 
worse -- than the market for the next 12 months, he says. Mesa recently 
announced an $18.2-million first-quarter loss and suspended cash distributions 
to holders of its preferred units. 
</P>
<P>
The company lost 24 cents a unit in 1989, contrasted with a profit of 52 cents 
the year before. According to Institutional Brokers Estimate System at Lynch 
Jones &amp; Ryan, an average profit of 12 cents a share is expected for Mesa 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
Q: In 1984 I bought 4,000 shares of Gemini Resources Inc. at about 40 cents 
each. Lately, I've been unable to find out anything about the stock. Do you 
have an address to write to? -- Hummelstown, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
A: I think you can kiss that $1,600 good-bye. The company's last address was 
878 E. Ninth St., Salt Lake City, Utah 84105. But there is no listing in the 
Salt Lake City telephone directory for a firm with that name. 
</P>
<P>
And the last time Gemini Resources stock traded over the counter was more than 
two years ago -- on March 22, 1988. It was then quoted at a bid price of just 
10 cents. JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052090-0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 221394 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 20, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
