</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, 1957 was "a golden year in a golden era for American consumers," and to 
a young Japanese boy moving with his family to the United States, the appeal of 
consumer imagery was epitomized by the new gimmick of putting advertisements on 
matchbook covers. Yosh Kashiwabara's collection, catalogued in "Matchbook Art" 
(Chronicle Books: $16.95; 120 pp.), records the boasts of many California 
landmarks, including L.A.'s Coconut Grove and Chili Bowls and San Francisco's 
Cliff House. These matchbook messages, carried out by the thousands in purses 
and trouser pockets, no doubt gave every businessman hope that the epithet 
"world famous," which appeared on such a large number of their establishments, 
would indeed soon apply. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
